WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:04.638 --> 00:00:06.171
Why are you making
a snack?

2
00:00:06.173 --> 00:00:07.840
We had couscous
an hour ago.

3
00:00:07.842 --> 00:00:09.942
Honey.
couscous is not a meal.

4
00:00:09.944 --> 00:00:12.244
It's an appetizer
with ambition.

5
00:00:13.481 --> 00:00:16.615
It's like
the Jeb Bush of food.

6
00:00:16.617 --> 00:00:20.185
(laughs)

7
00:00:20.187 --> 00:00:23.455
That is so funny.
You always make me laugh.

8
00:00:24.692 --> 00:00:26.792
What do you want.
woman?

9
00:00:28.062 --> 00:00:31.030
I had this idea
for our summer vacation.

10
00:00:31.032 --> 00:00:32.998
Well. if it's about
going camping in Wyoming.

11
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.335
that's my idea. but you can
take credit for it. Okay.

12
00:00:36.337 --> 00:00:38.404
I-I know you're gonna groan
when I say this.

13
00:00:38.406 --> 00:00:40.572
but I was thinking we could
finally go to Paris.

14
00:00:40.574 --> 00:00:43.342
(laughs)
You are so funny.

15
00:00:43.344 --> 00:00:45.377
You always make me laugh.
It's great.

16
00:00:45.379 --> 00:00:47.179
What is so terrible
about Paris?

17
00:00:47.181 --> 00:00:49.214
It's in France!

18
00:00:49.216 --> 00:00:50.716
Come on.

19
00:00:50.718 --> 00:00:51.884
I've been asking
to go there for years.

20
00:00:51.886 --> 00:00:52.751
And I've been saying "no"
for years.

21
00:00:52.753 --> 00:00:54.420
We're on a roll here. hon.

22
00:00:54.422 --> 00:00:55.587
No. no. no. Think about it.
Think about it.

23
00:00:55.589 --> 00:00:57.356
Paris in June.

24
00:00:57.358 --> 00:00:59.091
and I've been
learning French.

25
00:00:59.093 --> 00:01:01.193
so I already know how to say.
"You'll have to excuse him.

26
00:01:01.195 --> 00:01:02.661
He's American."
(chuckles)

27
00:01:02.663 --> 00:01:03.862
(sighs)

28
00:01:03.864 --> 00:01:05.731
Men are so frustrating.

29
00:01:05.733 --> 00:01:07.099
Oh. honey. I wish I could say
that feeling went away.

30
00:01:07.101 --> 00:01:08.567
-(sighs)
-Mm-hmm.

31
00:01:08.569 --> 00:01:10.069
Kyle and I are having
our first real fight.

32
00:01:10.071 --> 00:01:12.671
It's like a reality TV show.

33
00:01:12.673 --> 00:01:15.074
but with no music
to tell me how to feel.

34
00:01:15.076 --> 00:01:16.775
That<i> does</i> sound
like a reality TV show.

35
00:01:16.777 --> 00:01:18.177
That's why I'm totally
uninterested.

36
00:01:18.179 --> 00:01:20.279
What. uh. what was
the fight about. sweetie?

37
00:01:20.281 --> 00:01:21.847
The wedding.

38
00:01:21.849 --> 00:01:23.549
I told him I really wanted
to get married in our church.

39
00:01:23.551 --> 00:01:24.817
and Kyle really wants
to get married in his.

40
00:01:24.818 --> 00:01:26.084
He won't give in.

41
00:01:26.087 --> 00:01:28.420
No. Mandy.
you have to convince him.

42
00:01:28.422 --> 00:01:29.755
Kristin got married
in our church.

43
00:01:29.756 --> 00:01:31.089
It's a --
It's a tradition.

44
00:01:31.092 --> 00:01:33.058
The Baxter girls all have
their wedding there.

45
00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:35.661
How could it be a tradition
if just Kris got married there?

46
00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:37.930
We got married there.

47
00:01:37.932 --> 00:01:38.931
Oh. yeah.

48
00:01:41.202 --> 00:01:43.102
Okay. well.
one of you has to convince him

49
00:01:43.104 --> 00:01:44.754
because I already
tried my best.

50
00:01:44.755 --> 00:01:46.405
I texted him a sad face.
a church.

51
00:01:46.407 --> 00:01:47.723
a hot-air balloon.
and a cactus.

52
00:01:47.724 --> 00:01:49.040
and all I got back
was a question mark. so...

53
00:01:52.246 --> 00:01:54.546
You. uh.
you need to talk to Kyle.

54
00:01:54.548 --> 00:01:55.714
Why me?

55
00:01:55.716 --> 00:01:57.299
Well. because
he'll listen to you.

56
00:01:57.300 --> 00:01:58.883
He'll listen to anybody.

57
00:01:58.886 --> 00:02:01.720
He's like a smiling
satellite dish with a ponytail.

58
00:02:03.757 --> 00:02:06.758
--<font color="#ffff00"> Captions by VITAC</font> --

59
00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:10.496
♪♪

60
00:02:10.498 --> 00:02:12.097
Hey. Kyle.

61
00:02:12.099 --> 00:02:15.334
Look. I understand you and Mandy
had your first big argument.

62
00:02:15.336 --> 00:02:18.403
You finally have something
to talk to a bartender about.

63
00:02:19.306 --> 00:02:20.772
It was awful.
Yeah.

64
00:02:20.774 --> 00:02:21.940
It was like being
pecked at by a duckling.

65
00:02:21.942 --> 00:02:24.776
You want to love it.
but after a while.

66
00:02:24.778 --> 00:02:26.778
you're like.
"Hey. duckling. come on!"

67
00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:28.914
Okay.

68
00:02:28.916 --> 00:02:31.250
Well. get used to it.

69
00:02:31.252 --> 00:02:32.751
because marriage

70
00:02:32.753 --> 00:02:34.086
is just a series
of disagreements. you know.

71
00:02:34.088 --> 00:02:36.688
like how many kids to have.
where to live.

72
00:02:36.690 --> 00:02:39.024
is 100 bucks too much
to spend to keep a dog alive.

73
00:02:39.026 --> 00:02:41.994
I just don't like
fighting.

74
00:02:41.996 --> 00:02:43.095
Yeah. nobody does.

75
00:02:43.097 --> 00:02:44.329
Well. I do.

76
00:02:44.331 --> 00:02:45.764
but you got to pick
your battles.

77
00:02:45.766 --> 00:02:47.099
You know. win the ones
you want to win.

78
00:02:47.101 --> 00:02:49.201
and lose the ones
that don't cost you that much.

79
00:02:49.203 --> 00:02:51.003
So lose some on purpose?

80
00:02:51.005 --> 00:02:52.437
Exactly.

81
00:02:52.439 --> 00:02:53.772
Vanessa and I are having
an argument

82
00:02:53.773 --> 00:02:55.106
about where to go
on vacation. right?

83
00:02:55.109 --> 00:02:56.542
You know.
she wants to go to Europe.

84
00:02:56.544 --> 00:02:58.043
I keep telling her
I want to go camping.

85
00:02:58.045 --> 00:02:59.778
Oh. okay. So you're gonna
let her win this one.

86
00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:00.979
No.
I'm gonna let her lose.

87
00:03:00.981 --> 00:03:03.649
You just got to pick
your battles.

88
00:03:03.651 --> 00:03:05.284
Well. I have to pick
this one

89
00:03:05.286 --> 00:03:07.186
because I really want
to get married in my church.

90
00:03:07.188 --> 00:03:08.520
Why?

91
00:03:08.522 --> 00:03:09.955
Your church used to be
a roller rink.

92
00:03:09.957 --> 00:03:12.891
Six days a week.
it still is.

93
00:03:12.893 --> 00:03:15.460
It's just
your new pastor

94
00:03:15.462 --> 00:03:19.064
wants everybody to attend
premarital counseling.

95
00:03:19.066 --> 00:03:20.065
What if he doesn't think
we should get married?

96
00:03:20.067 --> 00:03:22.167
I wouldn't worry
about that.

97
00:03:22.169 --> 00:03:23.702
I don't know
the new pastor personally.

98
00:03:23.704 --> 00:03:27.406
but Vanessa and I
are. um. big donors.

99
00:03:27.408 --> 00:03:29.374
if you know
what I'm talking about.

100
00:03:29.376 --> 00:03:31.176
That's great.

101
00:03:31.178 --> 00:03:33.245
It's important to give blood.

102
00:03:34.548 --> 00:03:36.248
The truth is.

103
00:03:36.250 --> 00:03:37.849
I don't really know anything
about being a husband.

104
00:03:37.851 --> 00:03:39.851
You know. my dad wasn't around
when I was growing up.

105
00:03:39.853 --> 00:03:41.887
so I never had
a role model.

106
00:03:41.889 --> 00:03:43.922
You know. on the farm.

107
00:03:43.924 --> 00:03:46.091
we had a hog
who really loved his sow.

108
00:03:46.093 --> 00:03:47.359
but what if
Reverend Paul

109
00:03:47.361 --> 00:03:48.760
doesn't think
Gumball is enough?

110
00:03:50.231 --> 00:03:51.863
Sounds interesting.

111
00:03:51.865 --> 00:03:53.732
What are we talking
about here?

112
00:03:53.734 --> 00:03:56.168
Well. Kyle's a little worried
that the pastor at my church

113
00:03:56.170 --> 00:03:57.786
won't think he has
anyone in his life

114
00:03:57.787 --> 00:03:59.403
to teach him
how to be a good husband.

115
00:03:59.406 --> 00:04:02.641
and his best candidate
is a pig.

116
00:04:03.744 --> 00:04:06.245
Well. pigs are
intelligent beasts.

117
00:04:06.247 --> 00:04:08.981
which is probably why
they do not mate for life.

118
00:04:09.917 --> 00:04:11.149
You can cross Ed
off your list.

119
00:04:13.254 --> 00:04:15.187
I would make a great reference.

120
00:04:15.189 --> 00:04:16.955
I've been married 26 years.

121
00:04:16.957 --> 00:04:19.024
But not in a row.
and not to the same woman.

122
00:04:19.026 --> 00:04:21.426
Yes. well that's --
that's right.

123
00:04:21.428 --> 00:04:23.161
And I'm battle tested. see?

124
00:04:24.565 --> 00:04:26.865
This one here's spent
the last 30 years with his lady.

125
00:04:26.867 --> 00:04:29.434
skipping down
the yellow brick road.

126
00:04:29.436 --> 00:04:31.069
Well.
you got me there.

127
00:04:31.071 --> 00:04:32.838
Nothing more embarrassing
than a successful marriage.

128
00:04:33.741 --> 00:04:34.906
If your pastor wants to know
if you have a good role model.

129
00:04:34.908 --> 00:04:37.643
tell him you got the best one
in the world -- me.

130
00:04:37.645 --> 00:04:39.811
Hey. yeah.
That's right.

131
00:04:39.813 --> 00:04:41.647
Yeah.

132
00:04:41.649 --> 00:04:42.748
I mean. you certainly set
a better example than Gumball.

133
00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:43.915
Right.

134
00:04:43.917 --> 00:04:45.751
I don't want to be
where he ended up.

135
00:04:45.753 --> 00:04:46.785
-No.
-He's a farm animal.

136
00:04:46.786 --> 00:04:47.818
They're raised
for slaughter.

137
00:04:47.821 --> 00:04:48.920
Oh. no. no.

138
00:04:48.922 --> 00:04:52.324
He became my grandma's pet.
Hmm.

139
00:04:52.326 --> 00:04:54.726
She makes him wear pants.

140
00:04:55.663 --> 00:04:55.994
Excuse me.

141
00:05:00.234 --> 00:05:02.601
♪♪

142
00:05:02.603 --> 00:05:04.269
Hey. Eve.

143
00:05:04.271 --> 00:05:06.171
Your dad said I could
borrow this for the move.

144
00:05:06.173 --> 00:05:07.573
Got to take apart
a bookshelf.

145
00:05:07.574 --> 00:05:08.974
but the only tool I have
is a Swiffer.

146
00:05:08.976 --> 00:05:11.543
Okay.

147
00:05:13.314 --> 00:05:14.946
Wow.

148
00:05:14.948 --> 00:05:17.316
I leave myself wide open.
and you don't take a shot.

149
00:05:17.318 --> 00:05:18.250
Do you have a fever?

150
00:05:18.252 --> 00:05:20.752
It's my government class.

151
00:05:20.754 --> 00:05:22.037
We have this debate
coming up.

152
00:05:22.038 --> 00:05:23.321
and my teacher
is making us

153
00:05:23.324 --> 00:05:25.524
take the opposite side
of our political beliefs.

154
00:05:25.526 --> 00:05:28.860
which means
I have to be a...

155
00:05:28.862 --> 00:05:30.896
liberal.

156
00:05:31.832 --> 00:05:33.598
It's not a curse word.

157
00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.101
Well.
it is in this house.

158
00:05:36.103 --> 00:05:39.504
So I've been researching
liberal positions.

159
00:05:39.506 --> 00:05:40.772
I Googled "How to talk
out of your ass".

160
00:05:40.774 --> 00:05:42.841
but that was no help.

161
00:05:44.611 --> 00:05:48.013
By the way. never Google
"How to talk out of your ass."

162
00:05:49.616 --> 00:05:51.450
Well. I could help you
if you want.

163
00:05:51.452 --> 00:05:53.285
I love the art
of stating a thesis

164
00:05:53.287 --> 00:05:55.287
and making a cogent argument
to support it.

165
00:05:55.289 --> 00:05:56.722
I know.
It's the reason

166
00:05:56.724 --> 00:05:58.023
Kristin doesn't have
dinner parties anymore.

167
00:05:58.025 --> 00:06:00.726
Look. if you really
want to prepare.

168
00:06:00.728 --> 00:06:01.977
we should have
a mock debate.

169
00:06:01.978 --> 00:06:03.227
That's a good idea.

170
00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:05.797
You spew your usual garbage.
and I'll mock you.

171
00:06:05.799 --> 00:06:07.466
No. because then
you'll never learn

172
00:06:07.468 --> 00:06:09.401
how to defend
a liberal's point of view.

173
00:06:09.403 --> 00:06:09.901
That's because
it has no defense!

174
00:06:09.903 --> 00:06:11.069
Zing!

175
00:06:11.071 --> 00:06:13.405
How's that
for a cogent argument?

176
00:06:13.407 --> 00:06:14.906
First sign
of a bad argument --

177
00:06:14.908 --> 00:06:16.575
the need
for the word "zing."

178
00:06:16.577 --> 00:06:18.176
Look.
if you want to win.

179
00:06:18.178 --> 00:06:19.711
you got to practice saying
what a liberal would say.

180
00:06:20.581 --> 00:06:21.847
Okay.

181
00:06:21.849 --> 00:06:23.582
Hooray for taxes!

182
00:06:23.584 --> 00:06:25.084
Give me free stuff!

183
00:06:25.085 --> 00:06:26.585
White men suck!

184
00:06:26.587 --> 00:06:27.652
You mean like that?

185
00:06:29.022 --> 00:06:30.922
♪♪

186
00:06:30.924 --> 00:06:33.225
Ooh.
Look at these.

187
00:06:33.227 --> 00:06:34.760
The Eiffel Tower.

188
00:06:34.762 --> 00:06:36.261
Versailles.
and then -- and then

189
00:06:36.263 --> 00:06:38.597
we could head on over
to the Loire Valley.

190
00:06:38.599 --> 00:06:39.731
see some chateaux.

191
00:06:39.733 --> 00:06:41.600
Or we could go to Wyoming

192
00:06:41.602 --> 00:06:44.569
and go camping
in the Curt Gowdy State Park!

193
00:06:44.571 --> 00:06:47.072
The best of all state parks
named after an old sportscaster.

194
00:06:47.074 --> 00:06:49.741
I can't believe you're still
being so stubborn about this.

195
00:06:49.743 --> 00:06:51.543
Hey. what can I say?
You didn't marry a quitter.

196
00:06:51.545 --> 00:06:52.811
Neither did you.

197
00:06:54.014 --> 00:06:55.747
We have a problem.

198
00:06:55.749 --> 00:06:57.883
Our meeting with
the new pastor did not go well.

199
00:06:57.885 --> 00:06:59.251
What do you mean?
What happened?

200
00:06:59.253 --> 00:07:00.669
Kyle started saying

201
00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:02.086
all this crazy stuff
about being a husband.

202
00:07:02.089 --> 00:07:03.505
We talked about this.

203
00:07:03.506 --> 00:07:04.922
Didn't you explain to him
I was your role model?

204
00:07:04.925 --> 00:07:07.359
Oh. yeah.
I talked about you a lot.

205
00:07:08.429 --> 00:07:10.262
That was the crazy stuff.

206
00:07:10.264 --> 00:07:12.364
Oh. no. no. no.

207
00:07:12.366 --> 00:07:13.965
Nobody should repeat your father's
opinions except for your father.

208
00:07:13.967 --> 00:07:17.102
And (sighs) honestly.
even that's getting old.

209
00:07:17.104 --> 00:07:19.438
So here's the deal.

210
00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:20.906
Before he'll allow us
to get married in the church.

211
00:07:20.908 --> 00:07:23.742
Reverend Paul needs to meet
with you guys

212
00:07:23.744 --> 00:07:25.828
to talk about <i> your</i> relationship.
What?!

213
00:07:25.829 --> 00:07:27.913
You know. I'm already starting
to miss old Reverend Tisdale.

214
00:07:27.915 --> 00:07:28.980
You give him
a bottle of Bushmills.

215
00:07:28.982 --> 00:07:31.149
he'll do whatever you want.

216
00:07:31.151 --> 00:07:32.784
(sighs)

217
00:07:38.892 --> 00:07:40.892
So Reverend Paul
won't do the wedding

218
00:07:40.894 --> 00:07:42.594
because of something
you told Kyle?

219
00:07:42.596 --> 00:07:44.763
I want to talk
to his supervisor.

220
00:07:44.765 --> 00:07:46.064
Who's got God's number?

221
00:07:46.066 --> 00:07:47.766
Well. what exactly
did you tell him?

222
00:07:47.768 --> 00:07:49.067
I said to use us
as a role model

223
00:07:49.069 --> 00:07:50.569
because we have
a solid marriage.

224
00:07:50.571 --> 00:07:52.103
Yeah. and I told him
about all that great

225
00:07:52.105 --> 00:07:54.089
win-some. lose-some stuff
you taught me

226
00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:56.074
and how Mrs. B is gonna lose
the vacation argument.

227
00:07:58.946 --> 00:08:00.679
Really?

228
00:08:00.681 --> 00:08:03.648
That's when he started
writing stuff down on a pad.

229
00:08:03.650 --> 00:08:05.150
I'm gonna lose?

230
00:08:05.151 --> 00:08:06.651
I said you also win
some arguments.

231
00:08:06.653 --> 00:08:08.203
What else did I say?

232
00:08:08.204 --> 00:08:09.754
Yeah. that's true...
when he lets you.

233
00:08:09.756 --> 00:08:11.256
(scoffs)

234
00:08:11.258 --> 00:08:11.990
Which. I think.
is very generous.

235
00:08:14.595 --> 00:08:17.095
Or. as Reverend Paul put it.
"deeply disturbing."

236
00:08:17.097 --> 00:08:18.997
So he needs to meet
with you guys tomorrow

237
00:08:18.999 --> 00:08:20.098
before he meets with us again.
Hmm.

238
00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:23.468
-Come on. Kyle.
-Unbelievable.

239
00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:25.303
Unbelievable.

240
00:08:25.304 --> 00:08:27.137
They may not be able
to get married in our church

241
00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:28.773
because of you.
(sighs)

242
00:08:28.775 --> 00:08:30.342
You know how much
I wanted that.

243
00:08:30.344 --> 00:08:31.727
Exactly. which is why

244
00:08:31.728 --> 00:08:33.111
that's what
we should focus on.

245
00:08:33.113 --> 00:08:34.613
not who said what
to Kyle

246
00:08:34.615 --> 00:08:35.947
or who said they win
all the arguments.

247
00:08:35.949 --> 00:08:37.115
Yeah. both you.

248
00:08:37.117 --> 00:08:38.517
Okay. bottom line --

249
00:08:38.519 --> 00:08:39.985
we put up a united front

250
00:08:39.987 --> 00:08:41.953
to show the new reverend
that we have a perfect marriage.

251
00:08:41.955 --> 00:08:43.955
That is so funny!
(stomps foot)

252
00:08:43.957 --> 00:08:46.625
Yeah.
(giggles)

253
00:08:46.627 --> 00:08:46.992
You always
make me laugh.

254
00:08:46.994 --> 00:08:48.093
Yeah.

255
00:08:49.997 --> 00:08:52.898
♪♪

256
00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:54.232
Okay.

257
00:08:54.234 --> 00:08:56.568
Now we both have
our own podiums.

258
00:08:56.570 --> 00:08:57.903
Kris. we're ready.
(air hisses)

259
00:08:57.905 --> 00:08:59.638
It's kind of a crappy
debate stage.

260
00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:01.039
What is this. MSNBC?

261
00:09:01.041 --> 00:09:03.508
No. no.
Can't make those jokes.

262
00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:05.710
I am the conservative. and
you're the liberal. remember?

263
00:09:05.712 --> 00:09:06.711
Right.

264
00:09:06.713 --> 00:09:08.647
Rachel Maddow is my hero.

265
00:09:08.649 --> 00:09:10.582
(inhales sharply)
God. that leaves a taste.

266
00:09:10.584 --> 00:09:12.817
Okay.
here are the rules.

267
00:09:12.819 --> 00:09:14.819
You each have 30 seconds
for a response.

268
00:09:14.821 --> 00:09:16.321
When you hear this...

269
00:09:16.323 --> 00:09:17.722
your time is up.

270
00:09:17.724 --> 00:09:19.157
If you continue talking.
you will hear...

271
00:09:19.159 --> 00:09:20.926
(horn honks)

272
00:09:20.928 --> 00:09:23.828
And if you still won't shut up.
I am out of here.

273
00:09:23.830 --> 00:09:26.431
I'm not Megyn Kelly.
and I've got packing to do.

274
00:09:26.433 --> 00:09:27.032
Let's begin with a brief
opening statement.

275
00:09:27.034 --> 00:09:29.034
Ryan.

276
00:09:29.036 --> 00:09:31.903
America
is at a crossroads.

277
00:09:31.905 --> 00:09:33.905
Do we go the way
of Ronald Reagan.

278
00:09:33.906 --> 00:09:35.906
the greatest man with the
greatest hair who ever lived?

279
00:09:35.909 --> 00:09:38.243
Or do we follow
the lead

280
00:09:38.245 --> 00:09:40.278
of my weak-kneed.
socialist opponent

281
00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:42.614
who longs for the day
when ISIS rules the world

282
00:09:42.616 --> 00:09:44.082
and Americans
are in chains?

283
00:09:44.084 --> 00:09:45.917
What?
That's crazy.

284
00:09:45.919 --> 00:09:48.286
Nobody would say that.

285
00:09:48.288 --> 00:09:50.455
Conservatives say that stuff
all the time.

286
00:09:50.457 --> 00:09:51.823
We're lunatics.

287
00:09:51.824 --> 00:09:53.190
Are you gonna
take this seriously or not?

288
00:09:53.193 --> 00:09:53.992
Because I'd like
to get a good grade on this.

289
00:09:55.529 --> 00:09:56.695
Hey! I didn't even
get a chance to respond!

290
00:09:56.697 --> 00:09:58.296
(horn honks)
Oh. my God.

291
00:09:58.298 --> 00:09:59.865
Sorry.
You wasted your time.

292
00:09:59.866 --> 00:10:01.433
Okay. next topic --
entitlements.

293
00:10:01.435 --> 00:10:03.435
Uh. I'd like to go first on that one.
Mm-kay.

294
00:10:03.437 --> 00:10:05.036
Democrats have created
a nation of takers

295
00:10:05.038 --> 00:10:07.639
who live like kings

296
00:10:07.641 --> 00:10:09.274
and who have never done
a lick of work in their lives.

297
00:10:09.276 --> 00:10:11.276
My opponent may disagree
with this.

298
00:10:11.278 --> 00:10:12.544
but the best thing
we can do

299
00:10:12.546 --> 00:10:13.912
for the poor. elderly.
and disabled

300
00:10:13.914 --> 00:10:16.615
is to let them rot.

301
00:10:16.617 --> 00:10:18.517
Uh. thank you.

302
00:10:18.518 --> 00:10:20.418
Of course I disagree
with that.

303
00:10:20.420 --> 00:10:22.153
<i> Everybody</i> disagrees
with that.

304
00:10:22.155 --> 00:10:24.055
You know what? This whole
thing is stupid. Okay?

305
00:10:24.057 --> 00:10:25.890
You're just an angry.
malnourished vegan

306
00:10:25.892 --> 00:10:27.892
that is jealous
that I can eat cheeseburgers.

307
00:10:27.894 --> 00:10:30.562
So I quit.
This is stupid.

308
00:10:30.564 --> 00:10:31.596
I'm leaving.

309
00:10:31.598 --> 00:10:33.098
Oh. yeah.

310
00:10:33.100 --> 00:10:33.999
And Rachel Maddow sucks.

311
00:10:38.605 --> 00:10:40.772
Man. it is real easy
being a conservative.

312
00:10:40.774 --> 00:10:41.940
What is the matter
with you?

313
00:10:41.942 --> 00:10:43.942
That was my little sister.
and she needed your help.

314
00:10:43.944 --> 00:10:46.244
Trust me.
This is going to help.

315
00:10:46.246 --> 00:10:47.612
What? You see. I
have a theory --

316
00:10:47.614 --> 00:10:48.847
(horn honks)

317
00:10:48.849 --> 00:10:50.915
♪♪

318
00:10:52.019 --> 00:10:54.919
Okay.

319
00:10:54.921 --> 00:10:55.854
Reverend Paul
will be right in.

320
00:10:55.856 --> 00:10:58.256
-Ah. (chuckles)
-Thanks a lot.

321
00:10:58.258 --> 00:11:00.759
Hey. look at this.
Churches of Europe. Ugh.

322
00:11:00.761 --> 00:11:02.794
Maybe we should
borrow this

323
00:11:02.796 --> 00:11:05.630
to get a preview of what
we<i> will</i> be seeing this summer.

324
00:11:05.632 --> 00:11:08.633
Yeah. that's how
I want to spend my vacation --

325
00:11:08.635 --> 00:11:09.801
going to church.

326
00:11:09.803 --> 00:11:10.935
I hear ya.

327
00:11:10.937 --> 00:11:12.904
(chuckles)

328
00:11:16.309 --> 00:11:19.177
That'd be a little too much
like going to work.

329
00:11:19.179 --> 00:11:20.612
(both chuckle)
Hey. Reverend Paul.

330
00:11:20.614 --> 00:11:22.180
Really nice
to meet you two finally.

331
00:11:22.182 --> 00:11:23.948
Mike Baxter. You've probably
seen my name in the bibles

332
00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:26.117
right there by the words
"donated by."

333
00:11:26.119 --> 00:11:27.519
(all chuckle)

334
00:11:27.521 --> 00:11:28.787
You know.
for 50 bucks more.

335
00:11:28.789 --> 00:11:30.522
we can give you
a "written by."

336
00:11:30.524 --> 00:11:31.523
(both chuckle)

337
00:11:31.525 --> 00:11:32.957
-Uh. I'm Vanessa.
-Hi.

338
00:11:32.959 --> 00:11:34.693
We are so thrilled to have you
as our new pastor...

339
00:11:34.695 --> 00:11:36.194
Thank you.

340
00:11:36.196 --> 00:11:38.196
...and -- and I'm really
loving the contemporary service.

341
00:11:38.197 --> 00:11:40.197
Yeah. Yes. I've always
thought "How Great Thou Art"

342
00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:41.199
needed a guitar solo.

343
00:11:41.201 --> 00:11:42.333
(laughs)

344
00:11:42.335 --> 00:11:43.902
Well. please.
sit. sit. sit.

345
00:11:43.904 --> 00:11:46.337
You know.
we're also very excited

346
00:11:46.339 --> 00:11:48.173
about Mandy
and Kyle's wedding.

347
00:11:48.175 --> 00:11:52.210
Hopefully happening here
in our longtime family church.

348
00:11:52.212 --> 00:11:54.713
In pews we also donated.

349
00:11:54.715 --> 00:11:58.083
Well. Mandy and Kyle
are a lovely. young couple.

350
00:11:58.085 --> 00:12:00.418
Yeah. we think so. too.

351
00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:02.353
Well. looks like
we covered everything.

352
00:12:02.355 --> 00:12:03.922
We'll see you
at the rehearsal dinner.

353
00:12:03.924 --> 00:12:06.024
Um. why don't you have a seat
on that sofa

354
00:12:06.026 --> 00:12:08.159
that you may or may not
have donated?

355
00:12:12.499 --> 00:12:16.768
If your marriage is the model
for Mandy and Kyle.

356
00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:19.003
well. I have a few questions.

357
00:12:19.005 --> 00:12:21.005
Oh. we have a rock-solid relationship.
Mm-hmm.

358
00:12:21.007 --> 00:12:23.024
I mean.
we're gonna be the old couple

359
00:12:23.025 --> 00:12:25.042
who dies within minutes of
each other at the old-age home.

360
00:12:25.045 --> 00:12:26.044
face-down in our pudding.

361
00:12:26.046 --> 00:12:28.513
(laughs)

362
00:12:28.515 --> 00:12:31.349
Both chocolate!
Chocolate.

363
00:12:31.351 --> 00:12:32.984
Yeah.
that's how my parents went.

364
00:12:38.925 --> 00:12:41.593
Kyle mentioned
a vacation argument...

365
00:12:41.595 --> 00:12:42.927
Oh. ...and apparently you
don't want to go camping?

366
00:12:42.929 --> 00:12:45.697
Uh. well. no.
No.

367
00:12:45.699 --> 00:12:48.099
I mean. I would much rather
go to Paris and sit in cafés.

368
00:12:48.101 --> 00:12:50.401
drinking
amazing bottles of...

369
00:12:50.403 --> 00:12:51.503
coffee.

370
00:12:52.739 --> 00:12:54.205
We have disagreements...
Yeah.

371
00:12:54.207 --> 00:12:55.573
...but at the end
of the day.

372
00:12:55.574 --> 00:12:56.940
there's a balanced.
spirited give and take.

373
00:12:56.943 --> 00:12:59.277
I see.

374
00:12:59.279 --> 00:13:01.212
So might this be one
of those times when --

375
00:13:01.214 --> 00:13:03.081
how did Kyle put it? --
uh. you let her win?

376
00:13:03.083 --> 00:13:04.582
Listen.

377
00:13:04.584 --> 00:13:07.418
I don't want to say
anything bad about Kyle.

378
00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:10.155
so let's go
to the next question.

379
00:13:10.157 --> 00:13:12.374
(chuckles)
Well. hey.

380
00:13:12.375 --> 00:13:14.592
Don't be judgmental.
That's my job.

381
00:13:14.594 --> 00:13:17.428
Vanessa. do you ever feel

382
00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:19.931
that sometimes Mike can be
a little bit of a bully?

383
00:13:19.933 --> 00:13:21.733
(scoffs)
Wha--

384
00:13:21.735 --> 00:13:23.268
This woman buys $40 candles.
and<i> I'm</i> the bully?

385
00:13:23.270 --> 00:13:24.836
(scoffs)

386
00:13:24.838 --> 00:13:25.770
Please feel free to speak
if you want to say something.

387
00:13:25.772 --> 00:13:28.106
Well. I --
No. I mean. I --

388
00:13:28.108 --> 00:13:28.907
Honey. honey. why don't
we talk about this later

389
00:13:28.909 --> 00:13:31.676
at our favorite restaurant.

390
00:13:31.678 --> 00:13:33.845
the United Front?

391
00:13:33.847 --> 00:13:36.447
I'm starting to see
what Kyle meant

392
00:13:36.449 --> 00:13:38.917
about the pig
who wears the pants.

393
00:13:38.919 --> 00:13:41.119
No. no. no. no. no.

394
00:13:41.121 --> 00:13:44.689
That's an actual pig
in real pants.

395
00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:48.043
-Is it?
-Okay.

396
00:13:48.044 --> 00:13:49.928
All right. all right.
You know what?

397
00:13:49.930 --> 00:13:52.030
Look -- Look. I can clear
this whole thing up.

398
00:13:52.032 --> 00:13:55.099
My husband
is complicated.

399
00:13:55.101 --> 00:13:57.769
He's -- he's stubborn.
he's pushy.

400
00:13:57.771 --> 00:14:00.438
he has. like.
zero patience. and --

401
00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:02.574
Good job. honey.

402
00:14:04.945 --> 00:14:06.945
The man I married
is not perfect.

403
00:14:06.947 --> 00:14:09.314
But you know what?
Neither am I.

404
00:14:09.316 --> 00:14:10.882
And you have been
at this church

405
00:14:10.883 --> 00:14:12.449
for -- for. what.
all of two weeks?

406
00:14:12.452 --> 00:14:14.519
Okay. How -- how can
you possibly know

407
00:14:14.521 --> 00:14:15.119
what goes on between us?
Honey.

408
00:14:15.121 --> 00:14:17.622
Because we fit.

409
00:14:17.624 --> 00:14:20.058
We work.
We're perfect.

410
00:14:20.126 --> 00:14:23.595
In our marriage.
both of the pigs wear the pants.

411
00:14:26.199 --> 00:14:28.283
And -- and I don't know

412
00:14:28.284 --> 00:14:30.368
if I want someone officiating
in my daughter's marriage

413
00:14:30.370 --> 00:14:31.870
who doesn't believe in mine.

414
00:14:31.872 --> 00:14:33.004
Oh. and you know what?

415
00:14:33.006 --> 00:14:36.507
Your guitar service
is lame.

416
00:14:36.509 --> 00:14:40.345
You. sir.
are no Dave Matthews.

417
00:14:40.347 --> 00:14:41.913
Well.
Dave Matthews isn't stuck

418
00:14:41.915 --> 00:14:43.982
with Mrs. Osgood
as his organist.

419
00:14:45.685 --> 00:14:47.185
(chuckles)

420
00:14:47.187 --> 00:14:49.654
Oh. wow.

421
00:14:49.655 --> 00:14:52.122
Now you see how I end up
with $40 candles.

422
00:14:58.899 --> 00:15:02.367
Hey. Mike Baxter here
for Outdoor Man.

423
00:15:02.369 --> 00:15:04.002
What's the world's
most perilous journey?

424
00:15:04.004 --> 00:15:05.937
Scaling Everest?

425
00:15:05.939 --> 00:15:08.072
Crossing the Himalayas?

426
00:15:08.074 --> 00:15:11.910
The drive home
after eating Indian food?

427
00:15:11.912 --> 00:15:15.613
Dad. is that you?

428
00:15:15.615 --> 00:15:17.348
Nah. the most dangerous
expedition

429
00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:19.083
is where
one half the people quit

430
00:15:19.085 --> 00:15:20.285
and the other half die.

431
00:15:20.287 --> 00:15:21.352
Hmm?

432
00:15:21.354 --> 00:15:23.721
Yeah. marriage.

433
00:15:23.723 --> 00:15:25.857
And all the survival gear
I sell you won't save you

434
00:15:25.859 --> 00:15:27.759
if you marry the wrong person.

435
00:15:27.761 --> 00:15:29.727
You pick the wrong partner.
you find yourself

436
00:15:29.729 --> 00:15:31.763
in an episode of
"Naked and Afraid."

437
00:15:31.765 --> 00:15:34.565
only you'll rarely be naked.

438
00:15:34.567 --> 00:15:36.768
On the flip side.
you find your true life partner.

439
00:15:36.770 --> 00:15:39.237
and there's no mountain
or tundra you can't conquer.

440
00:15:39.239 --> 00:15:42.073
And you'll be naked
a lot more often.

441
00:15:42.075 --> 00:15:43.942
In Proverbs 21:9.
King Solomon wrote.

442
00:15:43.944 --> 00:15:46.611
"Better to live
on the corner of a roof

443
00:15:46.613 --> 00:15:47.946
than share the house
with a quarrelsome wife."

444
00:15:47.948 --> 00:15:52.250
And this dude knew wives.
He had 700 of them.

445
00:15:52.252 --> 00:15:54.152
That's a lot of anniversaries
to remember.

446
00:15:54.154 --> 00:15:57.388
God forbid you give Bathsheba
and Esther the same gift.

447
00:15:57.390 --> 00:16:00.992
(effeminate voice)
"Really? A straw hat?"

448
00:16:00.994 --> 00:16:02.927
(normal voice) And while
I appreciate the scripture.

449
00:16:02.929 --> 00:16:03.995
the truest thing
I ever read about marriage

450
00:16:03.997 --> 00:16:06.297
was on a coffee mug.

451
00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:08.833
It said.
"Happy Wife. Happy Life."

452
00:16:08.835 --> 00:16:12.103
Hasn't steered me wrong since
the day she threw it at me.

453
00:16:12.105 --> 00:16:14.872
♪♪

454
00:16:18.445 --> 00:16:20.945
Dad. you have to poke
some air holes in this one

455
00:16:20.947 --> 00:16:22.780
so my stuffed animals
can breathe.

456
00:16:22.782 --> 00:16:24.849
Boyd.
you are old enough to know

457
00:16:24.851 --> 00:16:27.685
that your stuffed animals.
they --

458
00:16:27.687 --> 00:16:29.420
Go get me the screwdriver.

459
00:16:29.856 --> 00:16:32.156
(knock on door)

460
00:16:33.526 --> 00:16:35.593
(rhythmic knocking)

461
00:16:38.264 --> 00:16:40.665
I knew you'd be back.

462
00:16:40.667 --> 00:16:42.667
I left my binder. so...

463
00:16:42.669 --> 00:16:44.002
You also left your dignity.

464
00:16:44.004 --> 00:16:46.537
All right. fine.

465
00:16:46.539 --> 00:16:48.773
I got mad. and by getting mad.
I automatically lost.

466
00:16:48.775 --> 00:16:50.008
Right.
Come in.

467
00:16:50.010 --> 00:16:52.443
Your teacher probably
wants you to learn

468
00:16:52.445 --> 00:16:54.178
how to have a rational
and civilized debate.

469
00:16:54.180 --> 00:16:55.613
Well. I don't know why.

470
00:16:55.615 --> 00:16:57.448
The crazy ones get
all the good ratings.

471
00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:00.385
Rational and civilized
aren't very popular these days.

472
00:17:00.387 --> 00:17:02.286
but it is still
worth learning.

473
00:17:02.288 --> 00:17:03.971
You know. you're pretty good
at this stuff.

474
00:17:03.972 --> 00:17:05.655
We're you ever on your
high school debate team?

475
00:17:05.658 --> 00:17:07.125
Nope.

476
00:17:07.127 --> 00:17:08.693
My training started
the very first time I said.

477
00:17:08.695 --> 00:17:10.528
"I don't think
I agree with you. Mike."

478
00:17:11.865 --> 00:17:12.964
Every argument.
he'd bait me. and I'd blow up.

479
00:17:12.966 --> 00:17:15.500
Yeah.
you used to get pretty mad.

480
00:17:15.502 --> 00:17:17.502
One time. soy milk
came out of your nose.

481
00:17:17.504 --> 00:17:19.237
And that's how I'd lose.

482
00:17:19.239 --> 00:17:22.073
But eventually.
I learned to keep my cool.

483
00:17:22.075 --> 00:17:23.041
And now you win some?

484
00:17:23.043 --> 00:17:24.075
Nope.

485
00:17:24.077 --> 00:17:25.910
But I keep my cool.

486
00:17:25.912 --> 00:17:28.413
All right. well.
if you're still cool with it.

487
00:17:28.415 --> 00:17:30.848
I'd love for you to coach me
on some liberal arguments

488
00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:32.717
so I don't throw up
during the debate.

489
00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:33.751
I would be happy to.

490
00:17:33.753 --> 00:17:34.886
Cool.
All right.

491
00:17:34.888 --> 00:17:36.587
Um. Obamacare.

492
00:17:36.589 --> 00:17:37.855
(inhales deeply)

493
00:17:37.857 --> 00:17:40.091
Obamacare
is the greatest thing to...

494
00:17:42.595 --> 00:17:44.095
No. I can't do it.
I'm gonna need a bucket.

495
00:17:46.199 --> 00:17:48.299
♪♪

496
00:17:49.035 --> 00:17:51.436
Vanessa?
Honey?

497
00:17:51.438 --> 00:17:52.537
(sighs)

498
00:17:52.539 --> 00:17:53.738
Hi.
What were you doing?

499
00:17:53.740 --> 00:17:55.073
Hey. well.
since we're gonna need

500
00:17:55.075 --> 00:17:56.908
to check out Kyle's church
for the wedding.

501
00:17:56.910 --> 00:17:58.709
I was looking
for my roller skates.

502
00:17:58.711 --> 00:18:00.344
(sighs)

503
00:18:00.346 --> 00:18:02.013
Look. I-I'm sorry about
what happened with the pastor.

504
00:18:02.015 --> 00:18:04.082
No. I think it was great
what you did.

505
00:18:04.084 --> 00:18:05.450
He was really
coming after us.

506
00:18:05.452 --> 00:18:06.584
and for someone
who loves France.

507
00:18:06.586 --> 00:18:08.419
you really held
your ground.

508
00:18:08.421 --> 00:18:11.355
Well. you know.
he was wrong.

509
00:18:11.357 --> 00:18:12.857
We make our decisions
together.

510
00:18:12.859 --> 00:18:14.759
You have always respected
my input.

511
00:18:14.761 --> 00:18:16.127
I do respect your input.
Yeah.

512
00:18:16.129 --> 00:18:18.196
But this time.
the decision's unilateral.

513
00:18:19.699 --> 00:18:22.366
"The Hopeless Romantic's Guide
to Paris"?

514
00:18:23.436 --> 00:18:25.036
I paid some lady to go buy that
at a bookstore for me.

515
00:18:27.941 --> 00:18:29.974
We're going to France.

516
00:18:29.976 --> 00:18:31.609
Oh. oh.
there's that bully

517
00:18:31.611 --> 00:18:34.612
that Reverend Paul
was talking about right there.

518
00:18:34.614 --> 00:18:36.814
Okay. okay.
but only under one condition.

519
00:18:36.816 --> 00:18:38.316
-No conditions.
-Yes. one condition.

520
00:18:38.318 --> 00:18:39.750
We're going --
we're going to France.

521
00:18:39.752 --> 00:18:42.086
We also find some nice
camping areas nearby.

522
00:18:42.088 --> 00:18:44.255
Deal.

523
00:18:44.257 --> 00:18:45.756
We'll take some cheese

524
00:18:45.758 --> 00:18:47.425
and a couple nice bottles
of coffee.

525
00:18:47.427 --> 00:18:48.426
Oh. yeah.

526
00:18:48.428 --> 00:18:49.927
(both laugh)

527
00:18:49.929 --> 00:18:51.762
As far as church
is concerned.

528
00:18:51.764 --> 00:18:54.132
I'll go have a little chat
with Reverend Bo Diddley.

529
00:18:54.134 --> 00:18:55.967
(sighs)
No. it's okay.

530
00:18:55.969 --> 00:18:59.137
Maybe -- Maybe we need
to start a new tradition.

531
00:18:59.139 --> 00:19:00.771
Like --
Like letting the kids

532
00:19:00.773 --> 00:19:02.840
figure out where they want
to get married themselves.

533
00:19:02.842 --> 00:19:04.842
Um. Reverend Paul
has a message for you guys.

534
00:19:04.844 --> 00:19:06.777
Yeah. I got a little message
for Reverend Paul...

535
00:19:06.779 --> 00:19:07.078
Uh...
...right about -- Hey!

536
00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:09.580
Hey!

537
00:19:09.582 --> 00:19:11.015
Welcome to our home.
(chuckles)

538
00:19:11.017 --> 00:19:13.851
I would've called earlier.

539
00:19:13.853 --> 00:19:16.687
but I like catching people
doing stuff.

540
00:19:16.689 --> 00:19:19.190
I-I need to apologize to you.
No. no.

541
00:19:19.192 --> 00:19:20.958
Not for what I said.
but for how I said it.

542
00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:23.661
Well. I think
we've all prayerfully considered

543
00:19:23.663 --> 00:19:25.063
what happened earlier.

544
00:19:25.064 --> 00:19:26.464
Eh. let's forget
the prayerfully stuff.

545
00:19:26.466 --> 00:19:28.049
You're not at work.
Sit down.

546
00:19:28.050 --> 00:19:29.633
Can I get you something
to drink? Wine? A wafer?

547
00:19:29.636 --> 00:19:30.034
Oh. no.
Thank you.

548
00:19:31.104 --> 00:19:34.505
I've realized that

549
00:19:34.507 --> 00:19:37.975
while part of my responsibility
is to teach.

550
00:19:37.977 --> 00:19:39.944
I also want to be that pastor
that listens and learns.

551
00:19:39.946 --> 00:19:42.513
And on the subject
of a strong marriage.

552
00:19:42.515 --> 00:19:43.114
I can definitely learn
from you two.

553
00:19:43.116 --> 00:19:44.982
(Chuckles)

554
00:19:44.984 --> 00:19:46.617
Just like
Kyle and Mandy have.

555
00:19:46.619 --> 00:19:48.186
Reverend Paul said we can
get married in the church!

556
00:19:48.188 --> 00:19:49.854
(gasps) Hey. that's wonderful.
Yeah.

557
00:19:49.856 --> 00:19:53.357
But he still won't let me
release 600 doves inside.

558
00:19:54.827 --> 00:19:56.460
Really appreciate
how this worked out.

559
00:19:56.462 --> 00:19:57.929
Butterflies?

560
00:19:59.499 --> 00:20:01.132
Kyle and Mandy's wedding
is gonna be very special.

561
00:20:01.134 --> 00:20:04.068
And it'll be the first reception
we have in the rec hall.

562
00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:05.670
Ah. you haven't been here
for very long.

563
00:20:05.672 --> 00:20:06.971
The church doesn't have
a rec hall.

564
00:20:06.973 --> 00:20:08.406
(chuckles)

565
00:20:08.408 --> 00:20:09.073
That's the other reason
I stopped by.

566
00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:17.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

567
00:20:20.186 --> 00:20:21.686
Hey. Mike.

568
00:20:21.688 --> 00:20:22.770
Hey. come on in.

569
00:20:22.771 --> 00:20:23.853
Just came by
to bring back your tools.

570
00:20:23.856 --> 00:20:27.258
Yeah. a man needs
his own tools. Ryan.

571
00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:28.926
I totally understand.

572
00:20:28.928 --> 00:20:30.094
That's why I got them back
to you as quick as I could.

573
00:20:31.397 --> 00:20:33.664
A man would've understood
what I meant there.

574
00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:37.101
Hey.
How was your debate?

575
00:20:37.103 --> 00:20:39.537
Great.
I destroyed Derrick Lowe.

576
00:20:39.539 --> 00:20:41.739
Good for you.
Did you keep it civil?

577
00:20:41.741 --> 00:20:42.907
Use the talking points
we rehearsed?

578
00:20:42.909 --> 00:20:45.276
Mm. actually.
I went another way.

579
00:20:45.278 --> 00:20:47.078
In my opening statement.
I reminded everyone

580
00:20:47.080 --> 00:20:48.412
of the time in third grade

581
00:20:48.414 --> 00:20:50.114
Derrick had to use
his emergency pants.

582
00:20:51.217 --> 00:20:53.584
(chuckles)
Classic.

583
00:20:53.586 --> 00:20:55.987
(air hisses)

584
00:20:57.924 --> 00:20:59.090
That's not debating.

585
00:20:59.092 --> 00:21:00.191
But it's winning.

586
00:21:00.193 --> 00:21:01.425
See.
that is the problem

587
00:21:01.427 --> 00:21:02.977
with conservatives --

588
00:21:02.978 --> 00:21:04.528
they don't debate. they insult.
Yeah.

589
00:21:04.530 --> 00:21:06.430
You know. I never noticed
how small your hands were.

590
00:21:06.432 --> 00:21:08.099
♪♪

